  <h2>Three Strategies for Navigating Roadblocks</h2>
  
  <h3>1. Reframe Obstacles as Design Constraints</h3>
  
  <p>When faced with a seemingly immovable obstacle, I've found success by changing my perspective. Instead of seeing roadblocks as failures or setbacks, treat them as design parameters that force creative solutions.</p>
  
  <p>For example, when limited funding prevented me from hiring a full development team for a client project, we pivoted to a modular approach that allowed us to build incrementally while generating revenue to fund future phases. This constraint ultimately produced a more thoughtful, user-focused product than our original all-at-once approach.</p>
  
  <h3>2. Build Resilient Systems, Not Perfect Plans</h3>
  
  <p>Early in my entrepreneurial journey, I believed detailed planning was the key to avoiding roadblocks. Experience has taught me that even the most thorough plans encounter unexpected challenges. The better approach is building systems and teams that can adapt when—not if—roadblocks appear.</p>
  
  <p>This means developing:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Financial buffers that provide runway when revenue fluctuates</li>
    <li>Cross-trained team members who can cover critical functions</li>
    <li>Modular processes that can be adjusted without complete overhauls</li>
    <li>Communication systems that surface problems before they become crises</li>
  </ul>
  
  <h3>3. Leverage Community Intelligence</h3>
  
  <p>Perhaps the most powerful strategy I've discovered is tapping into community wisdom. No roadblock you encounter is entirely unique—someone in your extended network has likely faced something similar and found a path forward.</p>
  
  <p>Building and nurturing a strong network of fellow entrepreneurs, mentors, and advisors creates an invaluable resource when obstacles arise. This isn't just about having people to ask for help; it's about gaining access to diverse perspectives that reveal solutions you might never consider from your singular vantage point.</p>
  
  <h2>Turning Roadblocks into Milestones</h2>
  
  <p>Looking back on my entrepreneurial journey, I can now see that the most significant roadblocks eventually became defining milestones. The funding challenge that seemed insurmountable led to a more capital-efficient business model. The key team member's departure forced us to document processes that ultimately made the company more scalable.</p>
  
